The paper discusses techniques for learning higher-order logic programs, which are relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The use of meta-interpretive learning (MIL) suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI), while the theoretical results and implementation in Prolog and ASP suggest a focus on logic and verification (cs.LO) and programming languages (cs.PL). The experiments on robot strategies and chess playing suggest a focus on computational learning (cs.CL), while the experiments on list transformations and string decryption suggest a focus on software engineering (cs.SE).
